Your code example doesn&#39;t really make sense as it doesn&#39;t represent true C# code. My presumption is that you are trying to compare C# DateTime variable types and may be getting confused that when these DateTime variables are being converted to strings as in your outputs, they may &quot;appear&quot; to be the same, but when testing for equality you are getting a false result. This is because what is stored for a datetime (raw binary data) and what you see when you write it to the screen (effectively calling .ToString()) are two entirely different things.

DateTimes are effectively tracking time down to roughly the millisecond, even if it doesn&#39;t output that when you print it. Because of this, you can have two DateTime values that look the same, but reflect different values.

To see this try outputting the total Milliseconds or the Ticks values from each of your values:

    Debug.Writeline(Time.Ticks);
    Debug.Writeline(contractNSQ100.Expiry.AddHours(-57).AddMinutes(59).Ticks);

I suspect you will get two similar, but different numbers.

When comparing date-times for testing purposes, first pick a threshold where the times will be considered equivalent. If you only care about the time down to the minute, then we can use Minute as the threshold. From there we compare the times:

    var comparisonTime = contractNSQ100.Expiry.AddHours(-57).AddMinutes(59);

    bool areSame = Math.Abs((Time.Subtract(comparisonTime).TotalMinutes) &lt; 1;

This will compare the two times and report back if they are the within 1 minute of each other. To determine whether they are within 1 second, change `TotalMinutes` to `TotalSeconds`. The `Math.Abs()` call affords the comparison to work whether the Time value is either slightly before or after the comparison time.

